# Zeta Conventions — Code Examples

Examples for patterns described in `zeta-conventions.mdc`. Read this
when working with smart-enums, view models, structural prop types, or
GraphQL inputs.

---

## Smart-Enum Consumption

From `useMultiSelectGallery.ts`:

```ts
actions
  .filter((x) => selectedItems.some((y) => y.operations?.includes(x.operation)))
  .map((x) => ({ ...x, label: x.label ?? x.operation.display }));
```

Permission check pattern:

```ts
operations.includes(Operation.comment); // YES
operations.includes('COMMENT'); // NO
operations.some((op) => op.value === 'COMMENT'); // NO
```

## View Models — Summary and Detail

```ts
export type MediaItemSummaryVM = {
  id: string;
  title?: string;
  createdAt: string;
  kind: MediaKind;
  status: MediaItemStatus;
} & ViewableItemVM;

export type MediaItemDetailVM = {
  id: string;
  kind: MediaKind;
  mimeType: string;
  title?: string;
  description?: string;
  originalFileName: string;
  createdAt: string;
  takenAt: string;
} & ViewableItemVM;

export function mapMediaItemToSummaryVM(mediaItem: MediaItemSummaryFragment): MediaItemSummaryVM {
  return {
    id: mediaItem.id,
    kind: mediaItem.kind,
    status: mediaItem.status,
    title: mediaItem.title ?? mediaItem.originalFileName ?? '',
    createdAt: mediaItem.createdAt,
    operations: mediaItem.operations ?? [],
    viewerIsOwner: mediaItem.viewerIsOwner,
  };
}
```

## Component Prop Types — Structural

```ts
export type GalleryThumbnailItem = {
  id: string;
  title?: string;
  thumbnailUrl: string;
  operations: Operation[];
};

type Props = { item: GalleryThumbnailItem; onClick: () => void };
```

Any value with at least these fields satisfies the prop type:
`MediaItemSummaryVM`, `PublicMediaItemVM`, etc.

## GraphQL List Input — Nested Shape

```graphql
input CommentsInput {
  collectionInfo: CommentCollectionInput!
}

input CommentCollectionInput {
  pageInfo: PageInfoInput!
  sortBy: CommentSortBy
  sortDir: SortDir
}

input PageInfoInput {
  limit: Int!
  offset: Int!
}
```

## Paged Query with totalCount via Window Function

```sql
SELECT
  id, target_type, target_id, /* ... */,
  COUNT(*) OVER ()::int AS total_count
FROM comment
WHERE target_type = :targetType AND target_id = :targetId
  AND parent_comment_id IS NULL AND deleted_at IS NULL
ORDER BY created_at DESC
LIMIT :limit OFFSET :offset
```

In the repository, extract `total_count` from any row and strip it
from individual records before returning:

```ts
const allRows = result.rows;
const totalCount = allRows.length > 0 ? Number(allRows[0].total_count) : 0;
const rows = allRows.map(({ total_count, ...rest }) => rest);
return { rows, totalCount };
```

## GraphQL Fragments — Bounded-Depth Tree

When a fragment references itself for replies but the depth is capped
(e.g. two-level), define a leaf variant:

```graphql
fragment CommentLeafFields on Comment {
  id
  body
  authorId
  displayName
  # ... scalar fields only
}

fragment CommentFields on Comment {
  ...CommentLeafFields
  replies {
    ...CommentLeafFields
  }
}
```

Top-level comments use `CommentFields`; replies use `CommentLeafFields`
because they're guaranteed to be leaves under the two-level cap.

## Mutation Response — IDs Only

```graphql
type AddCommentResponse {
  data: AddCommentPayload
  errors: [ContractError!]
}

type AddCommentPayload {
  commentId: ID!
  parentCommentId: ID
}
```

Resolver:

```ts
const result = await ctx.writeServices.addComment(input);
return writeResultToPayload(result);
```

Where the write service returns
`WriteResult<{ commentId: string; parentCommentId?: string }>` and the
helper maps success/failure to the envelope.
